 Aim I have got a garmin etrex gps which is very old but working pretty well; its major work is for sampling sites navigation in lakes/reservoirs.
By using GPSbabel, I can easily download/upload waypoints/tracks from gps devices under GNU linux.
 communication through rs232 protocal My workstation doesn’t have a serial port, so I use a usb2serial cable for doing this. In my case, I could find my serial device here:
{% highlight bash %} /dev/ttyUSB0 {% endhighlight %}
 download/upload waypoint For using GPSbabel, you will need to know how to do at least two things: read data from a file, and write it to another file. There are four basic options you need to know to do those things:
{% highlight bash %} Command Meaning -i format Set input format -f filename Read file -o format Set output format -F filename Write output file {% endhighlight %}
example 1: download from gps (garmin serial) and write to .gpx file
{% highlight bash %} gpsbabel -i garmin -f /dev/ttyUSB0 -o gpx -F waypoint.gpx {% endhighlight %}
or to .kml file
{% highlight bash %} gpsbabel -i garmin -f /dev/ttyUSB0 -o gpx -F waypoint.kml {% endhighlight %}
example 2: upload from .gpx or .kml file to gps
{% highlight bash %} gpsbabel -i garmin -f /dev/ttyUSB0 -o gpx -F waypoint.gpx {% endhighlight %}
or
{% highlight bash %} gpsbabel -i garmin -f /dev/ttyUSB0 -o gpx -F waypoint.kml {% endhighlight %}

 It is very time-consuming to write up the HEADLINE of your each post. This article is aiming to show you a bash command based way to set up the HEADLINE in the post.
#!/bin/bash ## ~/bin/wa hppath=&quot;~/u2/www/homepage&quot; d=`date &#39;+%Y-%m-%d&#39;` t=`date &#39;+%b %d, %Y %H:%M:%S&#39;` filename=${1// /_} head=&quot;---\n&quot; cd ~/u2/www/homepage/_posts/ postpath=&quot;~/u2/www/homepage/_posts&quot; # touch $d&quot;-&quot;$filename&quot;.md&quot;` echo -e &quot;$head&quot; &gt; &quot;$d&quot;-&quot;$filename&quot;.md vim &quot;$d&quot;-&quot;$filename&quot;.md Add execute permission on this file:
chmod +x ~/bin/wa Usage:
wa &quot;your article title&quot;
